Czech discovery: a substance that works on "hardening" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new combinations that can slow down the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also affects viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes precedence, in some cases, over the fact that the combination does not act so intensely on the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
However, the lives of patients can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
However, there are a number of side effects associated with their use.
Moreover, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what are called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to a way of dealing with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assemblage of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bonds on virus proteins.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages are formed by boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is indispensable to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
