Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Pneumococcal vaccination will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Voices are already rising, saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines to be paid by health insurance.
Specialists also see clarity in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for the children of August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococcal disease.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you'll have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year already a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
Yet parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that every year health insurance spends 300 to 450,000 kroons in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
Up to now, the State has spent about DKr 500,000 a year on all child immunization.
Reimbursed vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococcal infections cause inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
Hospital investigations indicate that there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 due to pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced the reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions on a possible obligation to vaccinate in the future.
From January, it must be regulated by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský said mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted pneumococcal vaccination.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose this at least.
I think this is a direction that must now be followed, Kalovský said.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination process.
We are not considering it at all at the moment, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeů.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that vaccination based on volunteerism has its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, one could envisage a decrease in vaccination renewals "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional," says Cabrnochová.
Specialists predict that as of next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Pneumococcal vaccination is also a break because it is the first vaccination of children that is funded by insurance and not the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should release funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their own products
This is, however, linked to the concerns of paediatric practitioners, which concern the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to have the vaccines purchased by insurance, with physicians receiving them in the same way as other vaccine products provided by the state.
However, some MEPs feared that this would allow insurance to "reduce the amount of health insurance".
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance to pay them back.
It is estimated that paediatricians will need to invest nearly 40,000 kroons per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It won't be easy, according to Cabrnochová.
