The United Nations group has draft emission reduction plans
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized so far by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned to the spotlight on Friday, due to the release of a paper highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations shouldering most of the burden, in the next few years.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as much as it has led the way.
But it was seen as an important step forward in the time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not say how rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging new economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of the global temperature increase that those responsible would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Sierra Club's Washington Representative.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the paper, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN Executive Secretary-General on Climate Change, Yvo de Boer, described as being "the complete picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, from 25 to 45 per cent compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to withstand floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States Representative on Climate Negotiations, rejected any discussion that required the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is getting harder on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, says Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei said that the US main negotiator, either lacked "good sense", or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the US would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than rescuing the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives of acting more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the main powers are fighting to find out who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make the major emitters responsible for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries, which are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change, have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that negotiations will lead at least to political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which brings together 43 members, drafted a proposal for a 24-page treaty, early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the Climate Unit of the European Commission, said that the action of the small island states has "put political pressure on the entire political process", partly because they are now unified and they are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend in camera meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be studied during the following week.
The real image of the gathering -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the convention hall every day -- guitar player activists present night shows mocking countries that they believe are betraying and proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and not later than Wednesday, 60 Heads of Government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats," said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavy goods vehicles are coming.
