But the 15th Correctional Chamber also ordered that a medical expertise of Liliane Bettencourt, aged 87, should be conducted collegiately by three doctors.
The heir and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre prosecutor's office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will be required to submit a report by March 10, 2010, stating in particular whether Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness and at what times.
I think she'll do it.
I'm going to talk to her, said Mrs. Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kijman, at the end of the hearing.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court's decision.
This is excellent news (...) The expertise will show that he (Mr.Banier) manipulated this elderly lady whom we must protect, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has brought criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and artist who she accuses of having taken advantage for years of her mother's weakness to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted being manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers to be a long-time friend.
While the court was due to consider the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers' case, the lawyers' pleadings sometimes turned into the great family unpacking on Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter dated 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Can you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
Françoise, I've never been able to talk to her since her marriage."
For her part, the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office again held that the complainant was not entitled to take action, especially since a guardianship judge had refused in recent days to grant her request to initiate judicial protection proceedings for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to take legal action, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in its place," said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court finally decided that it would decide once the trial had taken place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets to the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to a mortific demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the part that emerges from a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires on the part of employees a commitment that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns on the same level as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – like the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally manages, after many detours, to do primarily... what it has always done. !
- Second, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the United States "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reinforces the leaders in a posture of mechanistic governance, inappropriate to the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes a finalist view of human behaviour.
It consists in incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
At present, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this view of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and hand over their human resource management "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: "Just War" Worth Right-wing Praise to Obama
The U.S. right welcomed on Friday the speech delivered the previous day in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize laureate defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had lagged Obama's award on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice-president in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Ms. Palin, the geriatric right wing of the Republican Party, in the US Daily Today, adding that she herself had addressed the topic of war "sometimes necessary" in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is of course the last thing in my opinion that the Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We have to stop these terrorists all over there, she felt.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 additional soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, felt that the president had done in Oslo "a very good job".
I found that the speech was really good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected, considered by some as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush, a re-converted columnist at the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world" as "he always does", "he spoke as an American president", reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they have not created and that they do not do much to preserve it", Mr Gerson said.
Among the few on the right to be unconvinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, described the speech as "ternal, ampoule and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich alarmed that Barack Obama justified the use of force.
When one envelops war in the notion of justice, one can easily justify the massacre of innocent people, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained laudable for the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to think that the Nobel was prematurely awarded to Mr. Obama, called his speech "superproduction" even for an orator known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a road map to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression", has ignited the Californian daily.
Obama "made the right speech," the New York Times said, judging it "both dark and edifying".
Roads: three marathons for a deal that saves Christmas supplies
After three sessions of negotiations-marathon, the road trade unions and TLF, the only employers' organisation to have stayed until the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that put an end to the slogan of strike and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiced" this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators had left in the early morning of Friday, with the hope of early signing at the end of the morning.
Even though three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting begun at 11:00 a.m. for everyone to agree and for the text to be signed at 6:00 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very detrimental to businesses" and "it was to be feared that it would disrupt the end-of-year holidays," said Mr Bussereau.
The text provides for an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest wages (international transport).
In hourly rates, for low-wage earners, "we increase from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we're going very far, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we're going to order our militants that there be no blockades, no blockade of supply centres.
But we can still have some recalcitrants that aren't happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, praised "a good deal", although it was "difficult to concede increases on high wages given the international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros monthly for the low salaries and 100 to 120 euros for the highest salaries.
This is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) welcomed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) referred to "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs, and for the maintenance of general road transport in the first half of 2010, which will, in particular, address the question of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a 100 million euro reduction in employer's charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the 2009 draft amending finance law, which was adopted on the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "in the same terms".
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to be applied first to companies belonging to this organisation, and second, to the whole profession, in the event of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will take place "as soon as possible", assured Mr Bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "dupes market", as the €100 million "had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year, lamented the Unostra.
For the Otre, the agreement risks "to dig the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disruptions this weekend, unions dissatisfied with RATP proposals
Disruptions on the RER A, the largest urban public transport line in France, will continue during the weekend, while a meeting on Friday at the 2nd day of strike between trade unions and the management of the RATP left them on their hunger as to their demand for a bonus.
