The conflict threatens to expand to RER B on Tuesday, after advance notice is filed by Unsa and Independents.
The unions demand a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros including 30 euros variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, South, Independents) and complain about the deterioration of working conditions on this line to the daily million travelers.
The RER drivers, all in the second part of their career, receive from 2200 to 2700 euros gross and 600 to 650 euros of bonuses, for off-the-shelf hours, Sundays and public holidays.
Turkish justice dissolves the pro-Kurdish party, a decision with far-reaching consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court declared on Friday the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which had just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", the president of the Court Hasim Kiliç told the press, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to declare the dissolution, said Mr. Kiliç, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its President Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tuguk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Mrs. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's property.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabeled parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of obeying the "directions" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party assures that it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to describe it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict comes at a time when the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, in an attempt to undermine the Kurdish support for the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
DTP leaders had claimed that a dissolution could lead to an upsurge in tensions in south-eastern Anatolian, where numerous protests against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan have escalated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
As soon as the court announced, a thousand demonstrators gathered outside the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large southeast city populated mostly by Kurds.
Law enforcement officers fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, as protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with fronds.
A hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk claimed that the Justice decision would "intensify despair".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (kurd, ed) by banning a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This does not solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete torpedo of the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sandblasting service (FES) says that it is not to bother the citizens.
It is simply so that the agents can test the vehicle technique and learn how to master them.
And according to the meterologists, it might be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to attack snow and ice.
Here the FES follows a very elaborate plan.
Mr Brauburger explains that as soon as he starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel 20 main routes (known as routes A).
This includes busy streets, main arteries, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire access, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as the Atzelbergstraße.
FES officers begin duty at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometres of road must be salted with a well-attached road melter, within a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the FES service starts at 3 a.m. "so that roads are cleared when daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder, it's when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the road clearing and sanding department "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it no longer snows, access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße - are taken care of.
Secondary roads and side streets come last.
Mr Brauburger is well aware that this still causes a few complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the FES hiking team starts to clear priority areas deemed dangerous and crossings.
As for bike paths, FES services are generally unable to take care of them.
Mr Brauburger said that there was a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of the bridges between 10 and 4.30 p.m.
Since ice is formed very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
Police may also use this special service when needed.
The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 metres long for 1.50m tall, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine reports, Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the supercontinent's landline, the Pangea and was towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the early dinosaurs.
Indeed, he informs us about the family ties, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History of Utah and member of the excavation team tells that they sometimes find a dozen bones in one day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it after Tawa after the word of the Hopi Indians for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is a truly exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and are limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it can confirm some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which include the later tyrannosaure and the velociraptor, from which the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds on the long neck, and those related to them and the ornithische herbivores of which species such as triceratops and stegosaure are part.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species presents an interesting report of characteristics that are both primitive and developed, called S. Nesbitt.
Researchers found evidence that Tawa hallae had small aerial bags in its bones at the skull level, as did the birds that are the descendants of the theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small aerial bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed aerial bags and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers concluded that the Saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e., the whole of the land that formed the Pangea supercontinent.
This appears to be confirmed by the fact that the paleontologists team also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers advance.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine said there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, silesaure, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while there are virtually no fossils on other continents.
On the other hand, how did dinosaurs become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they originated from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch, remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the current crocodiles and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Trias dinosaurs spread all over the planet thus favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or the dinosaurs were better suited, so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favorite meteorite flourishing from a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and which since that time had been vegetating in the shadows: these were mammals.
Vienna Solidarity in Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley, California.
There are lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The police evacuation of the casino at Frankfurt's J.W. Goethe University is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and teachers from J.W. Goethe University as well as other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe and North and South America express their solidarity with the protestant students of the Westend Campus.
