The new "Silicon-valley"
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of search for secret weapons, under strict surveillance.
Today, with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
There are important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics.
As early as September 2008, representatives of Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, a place of the Francfortian sciences – with the academic institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of close collaboration".
The signatories were Deputy Mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz, Head of Project Section for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strength is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
This is a sustainable scientific exchange.
But also economic relations.
It will allow FIZ companies to enter the expanding Russian market.
On the other hand, Russian scientific companies want contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the seat of famous Soviet research institutes and societies.
There are the Moscow Institute of Electrotechnics, the major companies Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for arms research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") takes its name from the wooded hills at the heart of which the research centres are located.
Project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be placed high enough.
For his supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into hopeless chaos of construction sites for about ten years.
Stuttgart 21 was born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The head-end stations, with tracks ending in the middle of the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of 19th-century transportation technology that acted as a brake shoe for modern rail traffic as it once took a long time to get the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that's what you have to do.
That's why the head-end stations have to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And also in Stuttgart: a train crossing station, which is about halfway on the Trans-European Railway Magistral between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
Implementation of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners recognized that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, the head-end stations no longer pose any real problems of entry and exit since there are modern, reversible trains with railcars and pilot car at both ends.
However, Stuttgart 21 is now being launched next to the new route of the inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and communal policies prevailed.
The railway company is of the part because, it is the taxpayer who bears the risk of the largest infrastructure project in the Federal Republic and not the public enterprise.
From the urban point of view, this project is relatively justified.
We get an urban space that – according to the graphs of computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system the S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and the widening of the section are designed for a traffic of people to which one attributed - and it is typical of the 80s - a huge growth.
At the time there was still no competition for cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on increasing freight traffic because rail transport is much more environmentally friendly than trucking on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian project.
