75% of working mothers had work problems because of their maternity
Discrimination in the workplace has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have had a limited professional career due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of a couple's life and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not, and the type of job she is employed.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have little stable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back entry into marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving into a couple, and this figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector."These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of the beginning of a common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap in the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child later.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and tertiary education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years, respectively, on average.
"Another distinction also emerges between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado says.
