Sales of light commercial vehicles are increasing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market begins to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the Anfac and Ganvam manufacturers' employers' union, that of the dealers.
However, the good news should be qualified, since the reference for comparison in November 2008 was particularly bad, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the rebound of last month, the registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, by adding all vehicles that fall into the light commercial vehicle category (passenger car derivatives, pick-up trucks, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) 95,853 have been sold.
The large clouds that most affect their demand have not dissipated, because, although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100% of cases pay with external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions involved in limiting bank loans, other factors such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation must be added.
In the face of this situation and the difference between passenger vehicles, aid for the purchase of 2000E was scarce.
In addition to private individuals, independents and SMEs who wish to purchase a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a CO2 emission level not exceeding 160 grams per kilometre can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, at Ganvam, the need for the administration to pay particular attention to these vehicles and also to industrial vehicles (trucks and buses) was reiterated.
